userStories.notes:
The key insight: defineBrowserTool() is a pure identity function (definition.ts:28-30). Importing the compiled barrel evaluates all tool files, constructing BrowserToolDefinition objects with name/description/icon as plain strings. The generator simply reads those fields and ignores input (Zod schema) and handler (function). Side effects of importing the barrel are acceptable for a build script: Zod schema evaluation (~50ms), one readFile in version.ts (top-level await), and a wide-but-lazy module graph. No WebSocket connections or timers are started.

The generated file should look like:
```ts
/**
 * Auto-generated by scripts/generate-browser-tools-catalog.ts
 * Source: platform/mcp-server/src/browser-tools/*.ts
 *
 * Do not edit manually — run `npm run generate:browser-tools-catalog` to regenerate.
 */

export interface BrowserToolMeta {
  readonly name: string;
  readonly description: string;
  readonly icon: string;
}

export const BROWSER_TOOLS_CATALOG: readonly BrowserToolMeta[] = [
  {
    name: 'browser_clear_console_logs',
    description: '...',
    icon: 'eraser',
  },
  // ... all 40 tools
];
```

The script must use dynamic import() (not static import) since it runs via tsx and needs the compiled JS from dist/. The import path should be something like: const { browserTools } = await import('../platform/mcp-server/dist/browser-tools/index.js'). Make sure the script handles the case where dist/ doesn't exist (error with clear message: 'Run tsc --build first').

Create the platform/shared/src/generated/ directory. The barrel re-export in platform/shared/src/index.ts should be: export { BROWSER_TOOLS_CATALOG, type BrowserToolMeta } from './generated/browser-tools-catalog.js';

The root package.json build script currently is: tsc --build && npm run --prefix platform/browser-extension build:bundle && npm run --prefix platform/browser-extension build:side-panel && tsx scripts/generate-icons.ts && tsx scripts/install-extension.ts && npm rebuild @opentabs-dev/cli @opentabs-dev/plugin-tools. Insert the generator after tsc --build: tsc --build && npm run generate:browser-tools-catalog && npm run --prefix platform/browser-extension build:bundle && ...

IMPORTANT: The generated file must be committed to git (NOT gitignored). This ensures tsc --build works without running the generator first (fresh clones, IDE support, CI caching). The generator serves as both an updater (when tools change) and a verifier (catches drift during build).

The tsconfig for shared (platform/shared/tsconfig.json) should include the generated/ subdirectory in its compilation. Check that the existing include pattern src/**/*.ts covers src/generated/. If not, add it.

Also ensure the generated file is covered by a tsconfig for type-checking (check-tsconfig-coverage.ts runs during npm run check to verify all .ts files are type-checked).

In platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/App.tsx, change the initial state from:
```ts
const [browserTools, setBrowserTools] = useState<BrowserToolState[]>([]);
```
to:
```ts
import { BROWSER_TOOLS_CATALOG } from '@opentabs-dev/shared';

const [browserTools, setBrowserTools] = useState<BrowserToolState[]>(
  BROWSER_TOOLS_CATALOG.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: true }))
);
```

The BrowserToolState type (defined in bridge.ts:29 as ConfigStateBrowserTool) has fields { name, description, enabled, icon? }. The catalog's BrowserToolMeta has { name, description, icon } (icon required). Spreading the catalog entry and adding enabled: true produces a valid BrowserToolState.

When fetchConfigState() returns (App.tsx ~line 198-211), update the merge logic for browserTools:
```ts
setBrowserTools(prev =>
  prev.map(t => {
    const serverTool = result.browserTools?.find(s => s.name === t.name);
    return serverTool ? { ...t, enabled: serverTool.enabled } : t;
  })
);
```
Instead of the current: setBrowserTools(result.browserTools ?? []);

IMPORTANT: The disconnect handler (App.tsx ~line 269-281) currently resets browserTools to []. Change this to reset to the catalog defaults (all enabled) instead of empty — so the card stays visible during disconnect/reconnect cycles (stale-while-revalidating pattern extends to browser tools).

Actually, on disconnect the side panel shows DisconnectedState which takes over the entire main area — so whether browserTools is empty or populated doesn't matter visually. But keeping it populated means hasContent stays true, which is cleaner. Use: setBrowserTools(BROWSER_TOOLS_CATALOG.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: true }))) on disconnect.

The bridge.ts type BrowserToolState may need to be updated if the icon field optionality differs. The catalog has icon as required (string), ConfigStateBrowserTool has icon as optional (string | undefined). The spread { ...catalogEntry, enabled: true } produces { name, description, icon, enabled } where icon is string (not undefined), which satisfies both string and string | undefined.
